{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17565711","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17565711"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T23:30:56+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T23:30:56+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18281"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18281","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18281"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.35,0.01,0.28,0.13,0.24]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10995"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"105629"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10995","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10995"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18281"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"88074"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"26"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"160"},{"type":"tags","id":"1674"},{"type":"tags","id":"2706"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"4608"},{"type":"tags","id":"12917"},{"type":"tags","id":"12921"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"25543"},{"type":"contributions","id":"38569"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"105629","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/105629"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA medical emergency call is initiated for a 68-year-old woman on the surgical ward for hypotension. She underwent an elective total hip replacement five days ago and has been progressing slowly since then, with significant pain preventing her from engaging with allied health rehabilitation. She reports increasing dizziness and breathlessness over the past two hours. She has a history of hypertension and osteoarthritis. Her regular medications are amlodipine and paracetamol.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears distressed with cool peripheries. Her pulse rate is 120/min, blood pressure 85/50 mmHg, respiratory rate 28/min, SpO2 88% on room air, and temperature 37.8\u00b0C. Her jugular venous pressure is elevated at 6 cm. Her chest is clear to auscultation with no added sounds. Her calves are soft and non-tender. Her surgical wound is clean but there is mild erythema around the edges. Her fluid balance chart shows a 1500 mL negative balance over 24 hours with reduced urine output. Blood tests reveal:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHaemoglobin 98 g/L (115-165)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhite cell count 11.5 x10\u003Csup\u003E9\u003C/sup\u003E /L (4.0-11.0)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPlatelets 145 x10\u003Csup\u003E9\u003C/sup\u003E /L (150-400)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESodium 138 mmol/L (135-145)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPotassium 4.2 mmol/L (3.5-5.0)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECreatinine 145 \u03bcmol/L (45-90)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EC-reactive protein 68 mg/L (\u0026lt;5)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ELactate 3.2 mmol/L (0.5-2.0)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETroponin T 45 ng/L (\u0026lt;14)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely type of shock present?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Obstructive shock","Neurogenic shock","Cardiogenic shock","Septic shock","Hypovolaemic shock"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with features suggestive of acute pulmonary embolism causing \u003Cstrong\u003Eobstructive shock\u003C/strong\u003E. While there are features that could suggest other forms of shock, the combination of recent surgery, immobility, sudden onset breathlessness, hypoxia, tachycardia, and hypotension with elevated jugular venous pressure strongly suggests right heart strain from a significant pulmonary embolism. The clear chest examination helps distinguish this from other causes of shock.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHypovolaemic shock\u003C/strong\u003E could be considered given the negative fluid balance and reduced urine output. However, the elevated jugular venous pressure makes this unlikely to be the primary problem. The mild drop in haemoglobin is not sufficient to explain the degree of shock.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESeptic shock\u003C/strong\u003E could be considered given the mild fever, elevated white cell count, raised CRP, and wound erythema. However, these changes are common post-operatively, and the degree of inflammation is relatively mild for septic shock. The elevated JVP would be unusual in early sepsis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECardiogenic shock\u003C/strong\u003E might be considered given the elevated troponin, but this is likely due to right heart strain. The absence of pulmonary oedema and clear chest examination make primary pump failure less likely as the cause.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENeurogenic shock\u003C/strong\u003E from spinal cord injury would typically present with bradycardia and warm, vasodilated peripheries. The tachycardia and context make this diagnosis unlikely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe key to diagnosis in this case is recognising that while there are features that could suggest sepsis or hypovolaemia, the combination of risk factors (recent surgery, immobility) and clinical features (sudden onset breathlessness, hypoxia, clear chest, elevated JVP) point towards pulmonary embolism as the cause of obstructive shock. The elevated troponin likely reflects right heart strain, which supports this diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Obstructive shock from pulmonary embolism presents with hypotension, tachycardia, hypoxia, and often clear lung fields.","Recent surgery and immobility are significant risk factors for venous thromboembolism.","The combination of raised jugular venous pressure and clear lung fields helps distinguish obstructive from cardiogenic shock."],"references":["Holmes CL, Walley KR. The evaluation and management of shock. Clin Chest Med. 2003 Dec;24(4):775\u2013789. doi: 10.1016/s0272-5231(03)00107-2. Available at: https://doi.org/10.1016/s0272-5231(03)00107-2","Haseer Koya H, Paul M. Shock. [Updated 2023 Jul 24]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK531492/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"88074"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18281"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"88074","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/88074"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-06-11T09:33:51+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-06-11T09:33:51+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10995"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"105629"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"26","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/26"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd7c","name":"Critical Care Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"posi